sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M41006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Canosa, I., et al. "A Positive Feedback Mechanism Controls Expression of AlkS, the Transcriptional Regulator of the Pseudomonas Oleovorans Alkane Degradation Pathway." Molecular microbiology 35.4 (2000): 791-9. Van Beilen, JB, et al. "Analysis of Pseudomonas Putida Alkane-Degradation Gene Clusters and Flanking Insertion Sequences: Evolution and Regulation of the Alk Genes." Microbiology 147.6 (2001): 1621-30.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a sequence for hydrocarbon sensor. The input for this sensor is n-alkane chain and output is LacI. It has a sequence which encodes membrane protein (AlkL) and chemotaxis protein (AlkN) responsible for hydrocarbon sensing. This sequence does not code for any major alkane degrading enzymes except AlkL and AlkN.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This sensor is specific for our system. The output can be changed by removing LacI gene and adding other gene.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The original AlkN has promoter and ribosome binding site. We have only taken coding region for our system.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: lacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Coding region for the LacI protein with an LVA degradation tail and without an RBS. LacI binds to the pLac regulator BBa_R0010 and PLlac01 hybrid regulator BBa_R0011 and inhibits transcription. IPTG (Isopropylthiogalactoside) binds to LacI and inhibits its operation, therefore promoting transcription.

A rapid degredation tail (LVA) has been added to improve the High to Low performance of this part.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M.B., Leibler, S. A synthetic oscillatory network of transcriptional regulators. Nature 403, 335-338 (2000). [ELOW00]

References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M.B., Leibler, S. A synthetic oscillatory network of transcriptional regulators. Nature 403, 335-338 (2000). [ELOW00]

Sequence taken from the repressilator of Elowitz and Leibler (2000). The obtained sequence was compared to the wild-type sequence for LacI obtained through a database search. The sequence had been modified from the wild-type in that wild-type GTG start was changed to an ATG start (note, actual ORF in E.coli has several GTG starts it would seem). The LVA tag has been added for quicker degradation.

Incompatible with systems containing LacI, lactose, or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Grace Kenney, Daniel Shen, Neelaksh Varshney, Samantha Sutton

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M41002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Canosa, I., et al. "A Positive Feedback Mechanism Controls Expression of AlkS, the Transcriptional Regulator of the Pseudomonas Oleovorans Alkane Degradation Pathway." Molecular microbiology 35.4 (2000): 791-9
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: It is a first promoter of AlkS gene which is recognized by σS-RNA polymerase. It is downregulated by AlkS protein in the absence of alkanes, keeping the level of AlkS constant in the cell. When there are alkanes present in the cell, AlkS-hydrocarbon complex represses pAlkS1 and activates second promoter, pAlkS2, to produce more AlkS.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We cannot separate pAlkS1, pAlkS2 and AlkS gene because of self-regulatory system.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M41003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Canosa, I., et al. "A Positive Feedback Mechanism Controls Expression of AlkS, the Transcriptional Regulator of the Pseudomonas Oleovorans Alkane Degradation Pathway." Molecular microbiology 35.4 (2000): 791-9.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: It is a second promoter of AlkS gene. It is upregulated by AlkS-hydrocarbon complex formed in the presence of alkanes in the cell.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We cannot separate pAlkS1, pAlkS2 and AlkS gene because of self-regulatory system.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M41004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: AlkS coding sequence in Pseudomonas putida
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Canosa, I., et al. "A Positive Feedback Mechanism Controls Expression of AlkS, the Transcriptional Regulator of the Pseudomonas Oleovorans Alkane Degradation Pathway." Molecular microbiology 35.4 (2000): 791-9. Van Beilen, JB, et al. "Analysis of Pseudomonas Putida Alkane-Degradation Gene Clusters and Flanking Insertion Sequences: Evolution and Regulation of the Alk Genes." Microbiology 147.6 (2001): 1621-30.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This gene encodes a transcription factor AlkS, which activates alkane degradation operon. AlkS self-regulates its expression. In the presence of alkanes, AlkS forms AlkS-hydrocarbon (AlkS-HC) complex which downregulates pAlkS1 and upregulates pAlkS2. AlkS-HC complex activates pAlkB which is responsible for expression of alkane degradation operon.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We cannot separate pAlkS1, pAlkS2 and AlkS gene because of self-regulatory system.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M41005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Van Beilen, JB, et al. "Analysis of Pseudomonas Putida Alkane-Degradation Gene Clusters and Flanking Insertion Sequences: Evolution and Regulation of the Alk Genes." Microbiology 147.6 (2001): 1621-30. Canosa, I., et al. "A Positive Feedback Mechanism Controls Expression of AlkS, the Transcriptional Regulator of the Pseudomonas Oleovorans Alkane Degradation Pathway." Molecular microbiology 35.4 (2000): 791-9.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: It is an inducible promoter for alkBFGHJKL operon (alkane degradation operon). It is induced by AlkS-Hydrocarbon complex. The operon encodes different enzymes responsible for alkane degradation. Expression of the PalkB promoter is also modulated by catabolite repression depending on the carbon source being used.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: pAlkB is regulated by different carbon sources. When alkane is the only major source for energy in the cell, pAlkB will express the operon.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Hao Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
